1
00:00:57,516 --> 00:00:58,334
Ms. Wi!

2
00:00:58,334 --> 00:00:58,434
Ms. Wi!

3
00:01:00,352 --> 00:01:01,270
Hello.

4
00:01:02,813 --> 00:01:04,398
Hello.

5
00:01:05,065 --> 00:01:06,150
What brings you here?

6
00:01:08,402 --> 00:01:10,196
Oh, I had some business to handle.

7
00:01:14,033 --> 00:01:17,036
If you're done eating,
would you like to have tea with me?

8
00:01:17,912 --> 00:01:18,954
I…

9
00:01:23,125 --> 00:01:24,335
Shall we?

10
00:01:28,547 --> 00:01:29,590
I'll join.

11
00:01:34,386 --> 00:01:35,763
Me too.

12
00:01:36,388 --> 00:01:37,973
I'll join too.

13
00:02:14,969 --> 00:02:16,554
Let's sit over here.

14
00:02:22,935 --> 00:02:24,270
Here you go.

15
00:02:44,540 --> 00:02:46,542
The weather is so nice today.

16
00:02:50,796 --> 00:02:53,340
-What would you like to drink?
-I'll have an iced Americano.

17
00:02:53,424 --> 00:02:55,467
I'll have a hot Americano.

18
00:02:55,551 --> 00:02:56,427
And you, Mr. Lee?

19
00:02:56,510 --> 00:02:58,053
He'll have peppermint tea.

20
00:02:58,721 --> 00:03:00,472
You don't drink coffee
in the afternoon, right?

21
00:03:02,016 --> 00:03:03,559
Yes, I'll have a peppermint tea.

22
00:03:03,642 --> 00:03:04,810
Okay.

23
00:03:04,894 --> 00:03:05,811
I'll go and order.

24
00:03:05,895 --> 00:03:07,021
-No, I'll do it.
-I will.

25
00:03:07,104 --> 00:03:09,607
She'd feel uncomfortable
if her boss tagged along.

26
00:03:10,691 --> 00:03:12,735
-Go, now.
-Right.

27
00:03:12,818 --> 00:03:14,194
I'll go instead.

28
00:03:14,278 --> 00:03:15,195
Wait.

29
00:03:16,196 --> 00:03:17,865
I'd feel uncomfortable with an actor too.

30
00:03:19,491 --> 00:03:20,326
I'll go by myself.

31
00:03:36,008 --> 00:03:38,636
I gave you the chance on a silver platter.
What more can I do for you?

32
00:03:39,219 --> 00:03:41,805
But she said going with an actor
would be just as uncomfortable.

33
00:03:46,393 --> 00:03:47,394
Go now.

34
00:03:47,978 --> 00:03:49,063
Okay.

35
00:03:51,273 --> 00:03:53,275
-Be careful.
-Thank you so much.

36
00:03:56,862 --> 00:03:58,113
Here's your peppermint tea, Mr. Lee.

37
00:04:00,032 --> 00:04:01,200
Me first?

38
00:04:01,283 --> 00:04:02,284
Thank you.

39
00:04:08,499 --> 00:04:09,333
Thank you.

40
00:04:36,568 --> 00:04:37,945
The weather sure is nice.

41
00:04:39,405 --> 00:04:41,407
You've said that so many times.

42
00:04:49,915 --> 00:04:53,627
These flowers are called anemones.

43
00:04:53,711 --> 00:04:56,588
I heard they symbolize hopeless love.

44
00:04:59,049 --> 00:05:00,175
And they smell…

45
00:05:02,594 --> 00:05:03,887
enchantingly sweet.

46
00:05:08,183 --> 00:05:09,143
So sweet.

47
00:05:13,564 --> 00:05:16,025
How do you know such things?

48
00:05:18,193 --> 00:05:19,862
Because Kang Pil-gu likes flowers.

49
00:05:20,529 --> 00:05:23,365
You really must be a fan
to know that about him.

50
00:05:24,575 --> 00:05:25,576
Chief.

51
00:05:25,659 --> 00:05:27,828
So please take good care of Ms. Wi.

52
00:05:27,911 --> 00:05:28,996
Of course.

53
00:05:29,079 --> 00:05:31,874
I'll take good care of Ms. Wi.

54
00:05:32,958 --> 00:05:35,544
Didn't you win
the Korean Journalist of the Year award?

55
00:05:36,754 --> 00:05:40,174
I'm sure you'll be fine
without anyone's help.

56
00:05:40,257 --> 00:05:43,052
-Right?
-Yes, of course.

57
00:05:49,683 --> 00:05:50,517
Onion!

58
00:05:59,777 --> 00:06:01,236
Chief, do you use Onion too?

59
00:06:01,320 --> 00:06:03,989
Of course. It's a must if you have kids.

60
00:06:04,073 --> 00:06:08,243
You need it to buy and sell
barely used book sets or toys.

61
00:06:08,327 --> 00:06:10,579
What is this "Onion"?

62
00:06:13,165 --> 00:06:15,334
I've used Onion before.

63
00:06:15,417 --> 00:06:17,544
Ms. Wi, have you used it before?

64
00:06:17,628 --> 00:06:18,962
I use it pretty often.

65
00:06:20,214 --> 00:06:21,590
What did you buy most recently?

66
00:06:22,424 --> 00:06:24,676
Well, I got a TV for free

67
00:06:24,760 --> 00:06:26,970
-and bought a few necessities.
-I see.

68
00:06:27,054 --> 00:06:29,181
So what exactly is Onion?

69
00:06:31,600 --> 00:06:33,393
It's a secondhand selling app.

70
00:06:33,477 --> 00:06:34,728
Like an online flea market.

71
00:06:34,812 --> 00:06:35,854
I see.

72
00:06:37,481 --> 00:06:40,400
You wouldn't know
since you were born with a silver spoon.

73
00:06:42,069 --> 00:06:43,570
There are all sorts of apps out there.

74
00:06:44,279 --> 00:06:48,117
I hear people meet each other
through dating apps too.

75
00:06:48,200 --> 00:06:51,537
Some meet on apps, go on dates,
and even get married.

76
00:06:51,620 --> 00:06:53,038
Think of it as having

77
00:06:53,122 --> 00:06:56,125
a pen pal but in modern times.

78
00:06:56,208 --> 00:06:57,334
Some of them are jerks

79
00:06:57,417 --> 00:06:59,711
who hide behind their screens
and toy with your emotions.

80
00:07:00,212 --> 00:07:02,089
Tons of people do that
even after meeting in person.

81
00:07:02,172 --> 00:07:03,465
Imagine how much worse it is online.

82
00:07:04,883 --> 00:07:07,886
You shouldn't even think about
meeting people anonymously.

83
00:07:07,970 --> 00:07:09,054
You're right.

84
00:07:09,138 --> 00:07:10,013
I agree.

85
00:07:10,097 --> 00:07:13,267
I disagree. Weird people exist everywhere.

86
00:07:13,350 --> 00:07:17,062
It's a leap to assume
people like that exist only on apps.

87
00:07:17,646 --> 00:07:20,899
Don't you think some of those people

88
00:07:20,983 --> 00:07:24,278
have reasons they're unable to share?

89
00:07:24,862 --> 00:07:25,821
Right?

90
00:07:26,405 --> 00:07:27,322
Right.

91
00:07:27,406 --> 00:07:31,285
I assume married people
who sign up and pretend to be single

92
00:07:31,827 --> 00:07:33,495
wouldn't be able to share their stories.

93
00:07:33,579 --> 00:07:35,581
No, even on those apps,

94
00:07:36,415 --> 00:07:38,458
it's possible for people

95
00:07:39,001 --> 00:07:40,460
to really like someone.

96
00:07:41,962 --> 00:07:42,921
Don't you agree?

97
00:07:43,922 --> 00:07:46,216
-Move already.
-No, you go.

98
00:07:46,300 --> 00:07:47,426
Why do I have to go?

99
00:07:47,509 --> 00:07:48,719
Hey, it's Kang Pil-gu.

100
00:07:48,802 --> 00:07:50,679
-It's Kang Pil-gu!
-Let's get a photo.

101
00:07:51,638 --> 00:07:53,056
-Sorry, sir.
-Can we get a photo?

102
00:07:53,140 --> 00:07:54,892
-Sure, come here.
-I'm a big fan.

103
00:07:55,642 --> 00:07:56,602
I love your show.

104
00:07:56,685 --> 00:07:58,687
-Can I get an autograph too?
-Okay.

105
00:07:58,770 --> 00:08:00,564
We need a record
of this historical moment.

106
00:08:02,482 --> 00:08:03,692
One, two, three.

107
00:08:03,775 --> 00:08:04,651
What a great photo.

108
00:08:08,614 --> 00:08:09,448
Ms. Wi,

109
00:08:09,531 --> 00:08:11,450
if you're going back to the office,
why don't you ride with me?

110
00:08:11,533 --> 00:08:14,119
-I…
-Don't you have business in Gangnam?

111
00:08:16,079 --> 00:08:17,122
Yes.

112
00:08:17,706 --> 00:08:19,458
I'm going back to the office,
so I'll take your ride.

113
00:08:26,882 --> 00:08:30,010
Well, I'm going to Gangnam,

114
00:08:30,093 --> 00:08:31,428
so I'll take you there.

115
00:08:31,511 --> 00:08:32,679
No, that's okay.

116
00:08:32,763 --> 00:08:33,972
-It's okay.
-No, thank you.

117
00:08:40,687 --> 00:08:41,521
No, I'm fine.

118
00:08:49,279 --> 00:08:50,656
EPISODE 11

119
00:08:56,578 --> 00:08:57,537
Why are you driving yourself?

120
00:08:58,538 --> 00:08:59,873
I didn't think you'd want to

121
00:09:00,791 --> 00:09:02,125
get behind the wheel again.

122
00:09:02,209 --> 00:09:04,211
I can't quit driving
just because I was in an accident.

123
00:09:06,588 --> 00:09:07,839
Yes, you can.

124
00:09:08,423 --> 00:09:09,841
I'll drive for you.

125
00:09:15,264 --> 00:09:16,723
Lim Hyeon-jun and Wi Jeong-sin

126
00:09:17,349 --> 00:09:18,475
look quite good together, right?

127
00:09:24,439 --> 00:09:26,358
Are you saying the person Ms. Wi likes

128
00:09:27,276 --> 00:09:28,777
is Lim Hyeon-jun?

129
00:09:29,611 --> 00:09:31,613
I didn't look into it that far,

130
00:09:32,239 --> 00:09:33,073
but I can ask her.

131
00:09:33,156 --> 00:09:34,324
Forget it.

132
00:09:35,575 --> 00:09:36,827
Don't bother asking her.

133
00:09:45,877 --> 00:09:49,464
Why does Mr. Lee keep coming on to you?

134
00:09:49,548 --> 00:09:50,757
Come on to me?

135
00:09:51,675 --> 00:09:53,885
Why would you
disrespect his feelings like that?

136
00:09:55,887 --> 00:09:57,639
Are you taking his side?

137
00:09:57,723 --> 00:09:59,141
I'm not taking his side.

138
00:09:59,224 --> 00:10:01,435
You could've just said,
"I think he likes you."

139
00:10:01,518 --> 00:10:03,145
Did he say he liked you?

140
00:10:03,687 --> 00:10:05,647
Did he confess his feelings or something?

141
00:10:06,815 --> 00:10:07,649
Don't get carried away.

142
00:10:08,817 --> 00:10:11,028
So he did. I can tell that he did.

143
00:10:11,111 --> 00:10:12,654
So did you return his feelings?

144
00:10:12,738 --> 00:10:13,905
What's the matter with you?

145
00:10:14,406 --> 00:10:15,866
Mr. Lim Hyeon-jun, do you like me?

146
00:10:19,578 --> 00:10:21,455
I like someone else.

147
00:10:21,997 --> 00:10:23,582
And I'm still not over him.

148
00:10:24,416 --> 00:10:25,625
There's another guy?

149
00:10:25,709 --> 00:10:26,877
What do you mean "another"?

150
00:10:26,960 --> 00:10:30,672
Wow, you sure are a complicated woman.

151
00:10:31,256 --> 00:10:32,382
So complicated.

152
00:10:32,466 --> 00:10:33,467
What are you talking about?

153
00:10:51,026 --> 00:10:52,110
So where are you going?

154
00:10:52,861 --> 00:10:54,321
Why did you get out?

155
00:10:54,404 --> 00:10:55,238
What?

156
00:10:55,322 --> 00:10:57,574
People are recognizing you. Get back in.

157
00:10:57,657 --> 00:11:00,619
If they recognize me, then so be it.
Who cares?

158
00:11:00,702 --> 00:11:02,371
Are you worried a rumor might break out?

159
00:11:03,288 --> 00:11:04,581
I never said that.

160
00:11:05,957 --> 00:11:07,501
If a rumor spreads, then be it.

161
00:11:07,584 --> 00:11:09,002
Can't I even date at my age?

162
00:11:09,086 --> 00:11:11,004
But we're not dating!

163
00:11:12,923 --> 00:11:15,092
Anyway, who are you meeting today?

164
00:11:15,759 --> 00:11:17,094
An actor? Or a singer?

165
00:11:18,470 --> 00:11:20,931
If it's an actor, I can help you out.

166
00:11:21,014 --> 00:11:21,890
It's not an actor.

167
00:11:22,682 --> 00:11:24,726
Anyway, thank you for the ride. Goodbye.

168
00:11:24,810 --> 00:11:25,644
Wait.

169
00:11:26,228 --> 00:11:27,437
Ms. Wi…

170
00:11:29,106 --> 00:11:30,565
Jeez.

171
00:11:33,777 --> 00:11:35,695
-I'm a huge fan!
-Me too!

172
00:11:35,779 --> 00:11:37,489
This is amazing!

173
00:11:39,157 --> 00:11:40,534
-Thank you!
-Thank you!

174
00:11:40,617 --> 00:11:43,453
-We love you!
-We love you!

175
00:11:43,537 --> 00:11:46,415
-Love you!
-Thank you!

176
00:11:46,498 --> 00:11:49,292
I'll get a 15 cm Italian BMT

177
00:11:49,376 --> 00:11:51,128
-with the recommended combo.
-Sure.

178
00:11:52,212 --> 00:11:55,132
By the way, is the owner here?

179
00:11:55,215 --> 00:11:56,967
She stepped out for a minute.

180
00:11:57,050 --> 00:11:58,760
I see. Thank you.

181
00:12:07,894 --> 00:12:09,438
I already ate, but I can still eat this.

182
00:12:11,148 --> 00:12:12,023
This is good.

183
00:12:24,369 --> 00:12:25,287
Hello.

184
00:12:33,420 --> 00:12:34,296
This sandwich is good.

185
00:12:34,379 --> 00:12:37,132
That's good to hear.
So what brings you here?

186
00:12:39,134 --> 00:12:40,886
I came to ask you something.

187
00:12:41,511 --> 00:12:45,432
I recall Mr. Woo Young-suk's parents
had passed away,

188
00:12:46,224 --> 00:12:48,435
but he did have a living older brother.

189
00:12:48,518 --> 00:12:50,437
-Yes, that's right.
-Do you still keep in touch?

190
00:12:50,520 --> 00:12:51,813
No, hardly.

191
00:12:52,355 --> 00:12:54,441
We only speak when it's nearing
my husband's memorial day.

192
00:12:54,524 --> 00:12:57,319
But he really supported us
whenever things were looking tough.

193
00:12:58,069 --> 00:13:00,572
It sounds like the brother's well-off.

194
00:13:00,655 --> 00:13:02,657
We started out
in similar financial situations,

195
00:13:02,741 --> 00:13:05,160
but his restaurant business took off,
and he's doing well now.

196
00:13:05,744 --> 00:13:06,995
I haven't been there myself, though.

197
00:13:08,288 --> 00:13:12,584
Do you happen to know
where his restaurant is?

198
00:13:15,837 --> 00:13:17,756
He owns a place like this in Gangnam?

199
00:13:21,301 --> 00:13:22,219
Hello.

200
00:13:25,347 --> 00:13:27,390
I have a quick question.

201
00:13:27,474 --> 00:13:31,561
About that Cheongdam restaurant building
near the intersection.

202
00:13:32,312 --> 00:13:33,230
How much is it worth?

203
00:13:33,313 --> 00:13:35,106
-The building with the clock?
-Yes.

204
00:13:35,190 --> 00:13:37,984
It's worth about 40 billion won,
at the very least.

205
00:13:38,485 --> 00:13:40,111
Did you say 40 billion won?

206
00:13:40,654 --> 00:13:41,488
Yes.

207
00:13:43,615 --> 00:13:43,649
REQUEST TO VIEW
PROPERTY REGISTRATION CERTIFICATE

208
00:13:43,649 --> 00:13:45,075
REQUEST TO VIEW
PROPERTY REGISTRATION CERTIFICATE

209
00:13:45,158 --> 00:13:46,284
REVIEW REQUESTED CERTIFICATE

210
00:13:55,126 --> 00:13:56,044
What?

211
00:13:56,545 --> 00:13:58,797
MORTGAGE REGISTRATION

212
00:13:58,880 --> 00:14:00,590
MORTGAGE LISTED AS ITEM 3 RELEASED

213
00:14:00,674 --> 00:14:02,759
He bought the building entirely in cash,

214
00:14:03,385 --> 00:14:04,803
without taking out any loans.

215
00:14:18,233 --> 00:14:19,067
LEE DAE-HO, THE ENTERTAINMENT GIANT

216
00:14:23,405 --> 00:14:26,324
You probably didn't know
since you were new to the political desk,

217
00:14:26,408 --> 00:14:28,451
but there was a rumor at the time

218
00:14:28,535 --> 00:14:31,329
that Assemblyman Ha received land
from Lee Dae-ho under a borrowed name.

219
00:14:38,795 --> 00:14:42,549
So Lee Dae-ho bought land
under a borrowed name for Assemblyman Ha,

220
00:14:42,632 --> 00:14:44,593
but Ha Gee-wan doesn't have any assets
under his own name.

221
00:14:44,676 --> 00:14:46,886
His aide at the time died,

222
00:14:46,970 --> 00:14:49,264
and the aide's older brother
suddenly became filthy rich.

223
00:14:51,933 --> 00:14:52,976
What's going on?

224
00:15:05,697 --> 00:15:07,032
-Mr. Lim?
-Huh?

225
00:15:07,616 --> 00:15:08,742
Oh, Director Bak.

226
00:15:12,829 --> 00:15:13,747
Where are you coming from?

227
00:15:15,165 --> 00:15:16,207
Open the door.

228
00:15:17,876 --> 00:15:19,878
What brings you to my studio at this hour?

229
00:15:19,961 --> 00:15:21,046
Nothing much.

230
00:15:21,630 --> 00:15:24,215
I was in the neighborhood,
so I just stopped by.

231
00:15:24,299 --> 00:15:25,508
Would you like some tea?

232
00:15:25,592 --> 00:15:27,218
No, I'm okay.

233
00:15:28,470 --> 00:15:32,015
You see, I was wondering…

234
00:15:32,098 --> 00:15:35,393
if you could revise the part
about Kang Pil-gu becoming corrupt

235
00:15:35,477 --> 00:15:38,229
just a tiny bit?

236
00:15:39,397 --> 00:15:40,982
Have you read episodes nine and ten?

237
00:15:41,066 --> 00:15:42,776
Right, episodes nine and ten.

238
00:15:42,859 --> 00:15:44,903
Those were fun.
You did a great job writing.

239
00:15:45,528 --> 00:15:47,322
-Good work, so--
-That's good to hear.

240
00:15:47,405 --> 00:15:49,324
Two more episodes to go,
and then it'll be over.

241
00:15:49,407 --> 00:15:51,159
Well, before it ends…

242
00:15:51,242 --> 00:15:52,118
Oh, right.

243
00:15:52,202 --> 00:15:53,703
You know the date's been set for
our production press conference, right?

244
00:15:53,787 --> 00:15:57,082
Oh, the date's been set
for the production press conference?

245
00:16:01,169 --> 00:16:02,420
The production press conference?

246
00:16:02,504 --> 00:16:03,380
Yes.

247
00:16:04,339 --> 00:16:05,674
Wait, are you going?

248
00:16:05,757 --> 00:16:06,591
What?

249
00:16:06,675 --> 00:16:08,134
I'm the director,
so of course I'll be going.

250
00:16:08,218 --> 00:16:09,969
Come on, think about it!

251
00:16:10,053 --> 00:16:11,721
Every entertainment reporter
will be there!

252
00:16:11,805 --> 00:16:14,724
We can't tell them not to come!
What are we going to do?

253
00:16:14,808 --> 00:16:15,684
Of course, the reporters will…

254
00:16:17,185 --> 00:16:18,019
Ms. Wi Jeong-sin!

255
00:16:18,103 --> 00:16:20,480
That's right! Man, what do we do?

256
00:16:21,398 --> 00:16:22,982
-Then…
-Melomaster!

257
00:16:24,442 --> 00:16:25,568
-Yes.
-Yes.

258
00:16:26,528 --> 00:16:28,029
Oh, right.

259
00:16:28,655 --> 00:16:31,074
-Yes.
-I have a question, Melomaster.

260
00:16:32,992 --> 00:16:36,037
Who's the real Melomaster?

261
00:16:40,667 --> 00:16:41,835
No!

262
00:16:41,918 --> 00:16:44,963
Mr. Lim, what should we do?
We need to come up with a plan.

263
00:16:45,046 --> 00:16:46,715
Of course, we need a plan!

264
00:16:46,798 --> 00:16:47,966
Hurry and think of something.

265
00:16:50,427 --> 00:16:51,261
I've got an idea!

266
00:16:51,344 --> 00:16:54,681
How about we hold
the production press conference

267
00:16:54,764 --> 00:16:56,182
online instead?

268
00:16:56,266 --> 00:16:57,475
Hey, that's a good idea.

269
00:16:57,559 --> 00:16:59,352
Right, as if people
won't still see my face.

270
00:16:59,436 --> 00:17:02,897
Reporters will be watching
and writing articles in real time.

271
00:17:02,981 --> 00:17:04,441
That won't work then.

272
00:17:05,442 --> 00:17:06,484
How about this?

273
00:17:06,568 --> 00:17:08,319
You can disguise yourself
as an old man like last time.

274
00:17:08,403 --> 00:17:09,654
Great idea!

275
00:17:09,738 --> 00:17:11,072
I can't do that, Mr. Hwang.

276
00:17:11,156 --> 00:17:13,408
That's not something
anyone should do twice!

277
00:17:13,491 --> 00:17:15,618
Then what are we supposed to do?

278
00:17:15,702 --> 00:17:17,370
Byeong-gi, you're a writer.

279
00:17:17,454 --> 00:17:20,331
I'm sure you can come up
with a brilliant idea.

280
00:17:20,415 --> 00:17:22,167
Just think of something!

281
00:17:22,250 --> 00:17:24,127
It's hard enough writing scripts.

282
00:17:24,210 --> 00:17:27,088
Why should I have to worry about this
on top of everything else?

283
00:17:27,172 --> 00:17:29,716
How did I get caught up in this mess?

284
00:17:29,799 --> 00:17:31,843
Byeong-gi, you can do this.

285
00:17:31,926 --> 00:17:34,012
Just squeeze something out.

286
00:17:34,095 --> 00:17:35,555
How about a twin concept?

287
00:17:36,556 --> 00:17:37,557
What?

288
00:17:38,141 --> 00:17:41,603
I told her my name was Bak Jun-gi
that night at the N Seoul Tower.

289
00:17:41,686 --> 00:17:43,521
Bak Byeong-gi and Bak Jun-gi.

290
00:17:43,605 --> 00:17:45,940
If I get caught,
I'll tell her that he's my twin brother.

291
00:17:46,024 --> 00:17:47,358
That sounds like a plan, right?

292
00:17:47,442 --> 00:17:49,527
Hey, Director Bak!

293
00:17:50,069 --> 00:17:51,321
You're a damn genius!

294
00:17:51,404 --> 00:17:52,572
-Right?
-Yes!

295
00:17:54,157 --> 00:17:55,700
This is it!

296
00:17:55,784 --> 00:17:56,785
Hey!

297
00:17:57,494 --> 00:18:00,622
If you do that,
you two will end up on the news.

298
00:18:00,705 --> 00:18:02,290
How will you deal with the aftermath?

299
00:18:02,373 --> 00:18:03,666
She's a reporter.

300
00:18:03,750 --> 00:18:05,919
If you mess with her, she'll destroy you!

301
00:18:07,170 --> 00:18:08,797
He's got a point there.

302
00:18:08,880 --> 00:18:11,424
Yes, he does.
I think I lost my mind for a second.

303
00:18:12,634 --> 00:18:14,344
It won't work, Mr. Lim.

304
00:18:14,427 --> 00:18:16,888
Then what are we supposed to do?

305
00:18:20,892 --> 00:18:22,685
Director Bak.

306
00:18:22,769 --> 00:18:24,562
What is it?

307
00:18:24,646 --> 00:18:26,731
At first glance,

308
00:18:26,815 --> 00:18:30,902
fame might appear to be a good thing,

309
00:18:30,985 --> 00:18:33,279
but once your face becomes known,

310
00:18:33,363 --> 00:18:35,406
your private life is over.

311
00:18:35,490 --> 00:18:37,408
You know what I mean, Director Bak.

312
00:18:37,492 --> 00:18:40,453
I can't enjoy a meal in peace
when I'm out.

313
00:18:40,537 --> 00:18:43,331
What does that have to do
with the production press release?

314
00:18:43,998 --> 00:18:45,625
I'm just saying

315
00:18:45,708 --> 00:18:49,087
that it's best to be rich
and not be famous.

316
00:18:49,170 --> 00:18:51,923
Stop beating around the bush
and just say it.

317
00:18:52,006 --> 00:18:53,967
You don't want him
to attend the press conference.

318
00:18:54,050 --> 00:18:56,469
No, that's not it.

319
00:18:56,553 --> 00:19:00,056
I'm just saying
that instead of being somewhat famous,

320
00:19:01,057 --> 00:19:02,976
keeping a mysterious image

321
00:19:04,519 --> 00:19:09,232
and remaining a veiled, genius director

322
00:19:10,817 --> 00:19:14,028
may be an option for you.

323
00:19:14,112 --> 00:19:15,905
Mr. Lim, you're so selfish.

324
00:19:15,989 --> 00:19:18,324
Are you trying to block my career
because of your love life?

325
00:19:18,408 --> 00:19:21,160
I don't want to be forced
to stay an unveiled director.

326
00:19:22,370 --> 00:19:24,706
Who said anything
about blocking your career?

327
00:19:24,789 --> 00:19:26,791
You got it all wrong.

328
00:19:28,251 --> 00:19:29,294
Wait.

329
00:19:31,212 --> 00:19:34,007
What if we don't hold
a production press conference at all?

330
00:19:34,799 --> 00:19:35,925
Huh?

331
00:19:36,009 --> 00:19:37,468
I pray that we don't.

332
00:19:38,636 --> 00:19:41,931
Why do we have to do it
in the first place?

333
00:19:42,015 --> 00:19:44,601
There's nothing wrong with not doing it.

334
00:20:11,294 --> 00:20:15,006
These flowers are called anemones.

335
00:20:15,089 --> 00:20:18,593
I heard they symbolize hopeless love.

336
00:20:20,637 --> 00:20:23,264
And they smell enchantingly sweet.

337
00:20:26,935 --> 00:20:28,061
Why am I here?

338
00:20:31,981 --> 00:20:32,899
What?

339
00:20:33,691 --> 00:20:35,526
What the heck was that dream?

340
00:20:35,610 --> 00:20:37,362
What was that about?

341
00:20:37,862 --> 00:20:38,821
That was so weird.

342
00:20:41,908 --> 00:20:43,701
Mr. Lim Hyeon-jun, do you like me?

343
00:20:45,828 --> 00:20:48,206
I'll take good care of Ms. Wi.

344
00:20:48,289 --> 00:20:49,999
Are you worried a rumor might break out?

345
00:20:51,334 --> 00:20:52,877
If a rumor spreads, then be it.

346
00:20:52,961 --> 00:20:54,921
Can't I even date at my age?

347
00:20:55,004 --> 00:20:57,840
And they smell enchantingly sweet.

348
00:21:03,805 --> 00:21:05,890
I'm late.

349
00:21:06,599 --> 00:21:09,394
Gosh, this is a pretty hearty lunch.

350
00:21:09,477 --> 00:21:11,688
There's chicken, rice, and salad.

351
00:21:11,771 --> 00:21:12,772
It's pretty well-rounded.

352
00:21:12,855 --> 00:21:13,898
This is good.

353
00:21:13,982 --> 00:21:16,943
Yes, I'll be a bit more careful.

354
00:21:17,026 --> 00:21:18,361
All right, goodbye.

355
00:21:21,239 --> 00:21:22,615
How much longer
do I have to put up with this?

356
00:21:22,699 --> 00:21:23,908
What is it?

357
00:21:23,992 --> 00:21:25,785
I wrote about the markup
on idol photo cards,

358
00:21:25,868 --> 00:21:27,578
and got told off
for ruining the idol singer's image.

359
00:21:27,662 --> 00:21:30,832
It's their gimmick
that ruined their public image, not me.

360
00:21:30,915 --> 00:21:32,458
At least the PR team says it nicely.

361
00:21:32,542 --> 00:21:34,544
I recently wrote an article about a drama

362
00:21:34,627 --> 00:21:36,671
and got tons of hateful messages
from the actors' fans,

363
00:21:36,754 --> 00:21:38,256
filled with nasty swear words.

364
00:21:38,339 --> 00:21:40,383
Getting cursed at is part of being
an entertainment reporter.

365
00:21:40,466 --> 00:21:42,176
Getting cursed at is one thing.

366
00:21:42,260 --> 00:21:45,054
But when I write about
a celebrity scandal or suicide,

367
00:21:45,638 --> 00:21:48,891
I'm shocked at how I write it up
like it's not a big deal.

368
00:21:49,767 --> 00:21:52,020
Well, if it's that difficult for you,

369
00:21:52,103 --> 00:21:54,230
you could move
to a different department or media outlet.

370
00:21:55,314 --> 00:21:56,566
Why stay here?

371
00:21:56,649 --> 00:21:59,485
I loved watching movies and dramas
since I was a kid.

372
00:21:59,569 --> 00:22:02,363
Enjoying good media content as a viewer

373
00:22:02,447 --> 00:22:06,325
isn't the same
as stepping into that world as a reporter.

374
00:22:06,409 --> 00:22:08,828
And it may seem like
we only write gossip pieces,

375
00:22:08,911 --> 00:22:10,830
but there are celebrities
who reach out to thank us.

376
00:22:11,581 --> 00:22:13,833
Gratitude like that
is what keeps us going.

377
00:22:14,417 --> 00:22:16,544
I could ask you the same question.

378
00:22:16,627 --> 00:22:18,212
I thought you'd leave at the first chance.

379
00:22:20,381 --> 00:22:21,215
Well, I…

380
00:22:25,678 --> 00:22:26,804
I'm not sure.

381
00:22:26,888 --> 00:22:28,139
What did you say?

382
00:22:28,222 --> 00:22:29,390
What I'm saying is,

383
00:22:30,058 --> 00:22:32,894
instead of sending Ms. Wi
to the Kang Pil-gu press conference,

384
00:22:32,977 --> 00:22:35,772
would you mind sending
a different reporter?

385
00:22:35,855 --> 00:22:38,524
You called me all this way
just to ask me that?

386
00:22:39,734 --> 00:22:42,236
Circumstances came up, you see.

387
00:22:42,320 --> 00:22:43,571
When you ask a favor,

388
00:22:44,072 --> 00:22:46,407
you should explain
the circumstances first.

389
00:22:46,491 --> 00:22:48,284
Why are you so uptight?

390
00:22:48,367 --> 00:22:49,535
Consider how serious things must be

391
00:22:49,619 --> 00:22:52,371
for me, Lim Hyeon-jun,
to ask you this favor in person.

392
00:22:52,455 --> 00:22:54,165
There's no need to get emotional.

393
00:22:54,749 --> 00:22:55,833
Just explain it

394
00:22:56,459 --> 00:22:58,252
so that it makes sense to me.

395
00:23:04,258 --> 00:23:06,427
Well, something happened.

396
00:23:06,511 --> 00:23:08,387
It's too complicated…

397
00:23:09,430 --> 00:23:10,848
It's too complicated to explain.

398
00:23:12,767 --> 00:23:14,477
The truth is…

399
00:23:14,560 --> 00:23:16,312
This seems good enough to submit.

400
00:23:16,395 --> 00:23:17,772
Nice. Thank you.

401
00:23:22,819 --> 00:23:25,488
I hear you're doing an amazing job
here at the entertainment desk.

402
00:23:25,571 --> 00:23:26,697
Word has gotten around.

403
00:23:28,116 --> 00:23:30,868
I'm pretty exceptional, after all.

404
00:23:30,952 --> 00:23:33,746
So what brings you here all of a sudden?

405
00:23:33,830 --> 00:23:37,375
You're not here to ask me
to return to the political desk,

406
00:23:37,959 --> 00:23:38,960
are you?

407
00:23:39,043 --> 00:23:40,128
Actually, you're right.

408
00:23:40,837 --> 00:23:42,839
Really?
I'm returning to the political desk?

409
00:23:42,922 --> 00:23:44,006
Yes.

410
00:23:44,090 --> 00:23:44,924
But first,

411
00:23:45,883 --> 00:23:49,011
you need to destroy
all the videos you have,

412
00:23:49,095 --> 00:23:50,054
as if they never existed.

413
00:23:51,139 --> 00:23:52,348
You did what?

414
00:23:52,431 --> 00:23:53,558
-Onion.
-Onion!

415
00:23:54,976 --> 00:23:56,060
-Onion.
-Onion!

416
00:23:57,228 --> 00:23:59,021
Oh, that Onion.

417
00:23:59,105 --> 00:23:59,939
Yes.

418
00:24:00,481 --> 00:24:03,776
So the secondhand selling app
you said you've used before…

419
00:24:03,860 --> 00:24:05,820
Yes, that's right.

420
00:24:05,903 --> 00:24:09,031
I sold a rice cooker to Ms. Wi.

421
00:24:09,115 --> 00:24:12,827
Then the reason why Ms. Wi
looked strangely excited that day--

422
00:24:12,910 --> 00:24:15,204
Yes. She came out to meet me,

423
00:24:15,705 --> 00:24:16,914
but I'm not the one she met.

424
00:24:16,998 --> 00:24:18,583
I had someone else go in my place.

425
00:24:27,842 --> 00:24:30,553
I can't believe you did that on Onion.

426
00:24:36,017 --> 00:24:36,851
Oh, gosh.

427
00:24:39,270 --> 00:24:40,271
Seriously?

428
00:24:48,070 --> 00:24:50,323
Mr. Lim, it's a shame
to hear about your predicament,

429
00:24:50,406 --> 00:24:51,449
but there's no way around it.

430
00:24:51,532 --> 00:24:54,493
Regardless of whether
Ms. Wi attends the press conference,

431
00:24:54,577 --> 00:24:56,162
she'll see the photos taken there.

432
00:24:56,245 --> 00:24:57,830
Then what am I supposed to do?

433
00:24:57,914 --> 00:25:00,458
You and I agreed to team up,

434
00:25:00,541 --> 00:25:03,544
so you should suggest a solution
in a crisis like this.

435
00:25:03,628 --> 00:25:06,005
Imagine if Ms. Wi finds out I lied to her.

436
00:25:06,088 --> 00:25:08,174
Knowing her personality,
she won't stand for it.

437
00:25:08,257 --> 00:25:09,800
She'll swear never to see me again.

438
00:25:12,303 --> 00:25:15,056
If you get caught
trying to cover up this situation,

439
00:25:15,139 --> 00:25:16,265
it'll make things worse.

440
00:25:18,100 --> 00:25:19,310
Just tell her the truth.

441
00:25:21,103 --> 00:25:23,564
Why are you saying things
that don't help at all?

442
00:25:23,648 --> 00:25:24,941
That's not a solution!

443
00:25:28,319 --> 00:25:29,278
I want to

444
00:25:30,404 --> 00:25:32,156
stay at Sports Eunseong a bit longer.

445
00:25:32,740 --> 00:25:34,575
You're turning down
the investigative journalism team?

446
00:25:35,159 --> 00:25:36,577
But why?

447
00:25:37,078 --> 00:25:39,121
Don't tell me
you're still pursuing that case.

448
00:25:40,456 --> 00:25:41,999
No, it's not that.

449
00:25:43,668 --> 00:25:47,505
The entertainment desk has grown on me,
and it's been rewarding.

450
00:25:47,588 --> 00:25:49,131
Rewarding? Listen, you punk.

451
00:25:49,215 --> 00:25:51,926
They make you write up
30 to 40 articles a day here.

452
00:25:53,469 --> 00:25:55,638
Well, sometimes I get a dose of reality.

453
00:25:57,765 --> 00:26:00,393
But even if it's an article
that'll be forgotten overnight,

454
00:26:01,978 --> 00:26:03,437
there are readers out there

455
00:26:04,814 --> 00:26:06,440
who still want it and enjoy it.

456
00:26:07,275 --> 00:26:09,986
More than that, I feel more at peace
than I did at the political desk.

457
00:26:10,778 --> 00:26:12,029
So I'll stick around a little longer.

458
00:26:12,738 --> 00:26:14,198
I appreciate the offer you made.

459
00:26:15,116 --> 00:26:16,075
I'm sorry, Chief.

460
00:26:28,546 --> 00:26:30,798
-Yes?
-Hello, sir. It's me.

461
00:26:31,299 --> 00:26:33,968
I don't think we can get Ms. Wi to return.

462
00:26:34,051 --> 00:26:35,845
Why? Did she refuse the offer?

463
00:26:36,762 --> 00:26:37,680
Yes, sir.

464
00:26:39,515 --> 00:26:40,725
My apologies, sir.

465
00:26:40,808 --> 00:26:42,643
I trust you'll take care of that reporter.

466
00:26:42,727 --> 00:26:44,562
Stop her from causing more trouble.

467
00:26:44,645 --> 00:26:46,522
Yes, sir. Goodbye.

468
00:26:49,692 --> 00:26:51,277
I'm going to lose my mind.

469
00:26:51,944 --> 00:26:54,155
What if I end up
taking the hit from all this?

470
00:26:54,238 --> 00:26:55,948
Wi Jeong-sin, that punk!

471
00:26:59,452 --> 00:27:02,079
These clothes aren't really my style.

472
00:27:03,831 --> 00:27:05,207
Let's check out that place.

473
00:27:05,291 --> 00:27:06,500
-That one?
-Yeah.

474
00:27:19,263 --> 00:27:20,264
PRICE: 1,860,000 WON

475
00:27:21,390 --> 00:27:22,224
One million eight hundred…

476
00:27:23,684 --> 00:27:25,770
Jeong-sin, it's way too expensive here.

477
00:27:25,853 --> 00:27:26,854
Let's go somewhere else.

478
00:27:26,937 --> 00:27:29,190
Hey, don't be a chicken
and just choose one.

479
00:27:29,857 --> 00:27:32,109
Look at the price of this
before telling me not to chicken out.

480
00:27:32,193 --> 00:27:35,404
Choose one while I'm offering.
This is a rare opportunity.

481
00:27:38,282 --> 00:27:39,283
Then can I get this?

482
00:27:40,409 --> 00:27:41,577
-This one?
-Yes.

483
00:27:42,620 --> 00:27:43,496
Let's take a look.

484
00:27:44,705 --> 00:27:47,291
-It looks nice.
-And it's the perfect size.

485
00:27:47,375 --> 00:27:48,417
I knew you wanted it.

486
00:27:54,090 --> 00:27:55,508
Do you offer a 12-month payment plan?

487
00:27:55,591 --> 00:27:56,759
Yes.

488
00:27:58,636 --> 00:27:59,595
Thanks for this.

489
00:28:02,640 --> 00:28:04,683
You probably spent
about a month's paycheck.

490
00:28:04,767 --> 00:28:05,810
Are you sure this is okay?

491
00:28:05,893 --> 00:28:07,603
Of course. That's why I got it for you.

492
00:28:08,729 --> 00:28:11,273
You always nag me whenever I spend money.

493
00:28:11,357 --> 00:28:12,400
Why splurge today?

494
00:28:13,067 --> 00:28:15,778
It's not like I didn't want to get you

495
00:28:15,861 --> 00:28:18,030
nice clothes and shoes
at a place like this.

496
00:28:18,114 --> 00:28:21,075
We have no parents or relatives
who would give us money.

497
00:28:21,158 --> 00:28:23,160
I don't want to ask anyone for help,

498
00:28:24,036 --> 00:28:25,871
so I just have to cut back a bit.

499
00:28:27,373 --> 00:28:28,374
Be good to me, you brat!

500
00:28:29,458 --> 00:28:30,292
Yes, ma'am.

501
00:28:32,461 --> 00:28:33,379
Here, have a drink.

502
00:28:39,176 --> 00:28:40,261
-Cheers.
-Cheers.

503
00:28:45,516 --> 00:28:47,226
It seems like only yesterday
that you were a kid.

504
00:28:47,768 --> 00:28:50,521
Now look at us, drinking together.
How touching.

505
00:28:50,604 --> 00:28:52,565
Jeez, stop being so dramatic.

506
00:28:53,107 --> 00:28:56,444
Hey, do you remember
how I was a high school senior

507
00:28:56,527 --> 00:28:58,028
when you started elementary school?

508
00:28:58,112 --> 00:28:59,697
You'll never imagine
how hectic it was for me.

509
00:28:59,780 --> 00:29:04,285
Yet I still got into Hankuk University.
Aren't you proud of your big sister?

510
00:29:04,368 --> 00:29:06,871
Wow, you never fail
to turn things into a brag about yourself.

511
00:29:08,038 --> 00:29:08,998
Oh, right.

512
00:29:09,081 --> 00:29:10,833
-The press conference is tomorrow, right?
-Yeah.

513
00:29:11,709 --> 00:29:12,877
Are you attending?

514
00:29:12,960 --> 00:29:14,253
No, I'm not part of that.

515
00:29:16,255 --> 00:29:17,715
I wonder when I'll get to attend.

516
00:29:17,798 --> 00:29:19,884
Learn from me and work hard.

517
00:29:19,967 --> 00:29:21,302
Your day will come then.

518
00:29:21,802 --> 00:29:22,636
Sure.

519
00:29:23,220 --> 00:29:26,474
By the way, is it over with that guy
you were flirting with?

520
00:29:27,099 --> 00:29:28,058
What are you talking about?

521
00:29:28,142 --> 00:29:32,271
Remember the bro at work
who handed you the gimbap?

522
00:29:32,771 --> 00:29:33,981
Why do you call every guy "bro"?

523
00:29:34,565 --> 00:29:36,942
He's the president of our company!

524
00:29:37,026 --> 00:29:38,027
The president?

525
00:29:38,861 --> 00:29:40,863
That young, handsome guy is the president?

526
